00:46:12.220 --> 00:46:13.960
I would have to
discuss with you then

00:46:13.960 --> 00:46:16.900
after we have done the
plenary session here.

00:46:16.900 --> 00:46:17.830
I'm happy to do so.

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:22.790
- I find you so
intelligent, and thank you,

00:46:22.790 --> 00:46:25.080
thank you for all you've stated.

00:46:25.080 --> 00:46:25.580
However--

00:46:25.580 --> 00:46:26.480
- Tell my wife.

00:46:26.480 --> 00:46:29.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:29.690 --> 00:46:32.120
- I have had my
first knee surgery,

00:46:32.120 --> 00:46:36.320
and in my physical therapy
five and three times a week,

00:46:36.320 --> 00:46:41.750
they always bring up
blood up to my knee.

00:46:41.750 --> 00:46:46.080
And you stated about
the blood in our head.

00:46:46.080 --> 00:46:48.920
So again, if we bring
up blood, is that

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:51.510
going to make a difference?

00:46:51.510 --> 00:46:53.770
- Well, you see, yes.

00:46:53.770 --> 00:46:56.410
The answer is yes.

00:46:56.410 --> 00:47:01.040
Your brain is the
organ that needs,

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:03.890
proportionately
speaking, most oxygen.

00:47:03.890 --> 00:47:08.600
You can do with a lot of
less oxygen in your heart,

00:47:08.600 --> 00:47:10.550
your liver, but your brain, no.

00:47:10.550 --> 00:47:12.590
It needs to really
a lot of oxygen.

00:47:12.590 --> 00:47:16.130
So the moment you're
awake, you need it,

00:47:16.130 --> 00:47:17.630
and if you don't
have it, something

00:47:17.630 --> 00:47:19.375
goes wrong with
these neuron cells.

00:47:19.375 --> 00:47:20.860
It's as simple as that.

00:47:20.860 --> 00:47:25.910
Your knee is probably better
without a bit more blood.

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:27.290
- I'm in my 70s.

00:47:27.290 --> 00:47:28.951
I'm old, and I don't
want to grow up.

00:47:28.951 --> 00:47:29.450
Thank you.

00:47:29.450 --> 00:47:32.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:32.330 --> 00:47:34.280
- I have-- pleasure to
listen to you today.

00:47:34.280 --> 00:47:36.760
I have two fairly
pointed questions.

00:47:36.760 --> 00:47:42.750
One, what are your
thoughts on EDTA chelation,

00:47:42.750 --> 00:47:47.190
if there are atherosclerotic
conditions that are affecting

00:47:47.190 --> 00:47:50.690
brain perfusion, and
then number two, what

00:47:50.690 --> 00:47:53.850
are your thoughts on
things like [? HydroGene ?]

00:47:53.850 --> 00:47:59.520
or the racetams for increasing
blood flow to the brain?

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:02.190
Ginkgo biloba-- and of course,
there's a million supplements,

00:48:02.190 --> 00:48:04.050
but I'm particularly
curious about what

00:48:04.050 --> 00:48:07.050
you thought about
[? HydroGene ?] and EDTA,

00:48:07.050 --> 00:48:11.380
given that they're both
fairly inexpensive and safe.

00:48:11.380 --> 00:48:14.370
- Well, I appreciate
the general question.

00:48:14.370 --> 00:48:19.050
Namely, are there
relatively simple ways

00:48:19.050 --> 00:48:25.980
to increase blood flow here or
to reduce the negative effects

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:28.620
that we have on
our blood vessels?

00:48:28.620 --> 00:48:31.950
And you think of a kind of
omnibus type of effect--

00:48:31.950 --> 00:48:34.880
a big effect on the overall
circulation and then

00:48:34.880 --> 00:48:35.800
on the brain.

00:48:35.800 --> 00:48:39.990
My favorite one there
is, indeed, antioxidants,

00:48:39.990 --> 00:48:44.040
because the free radicals--

00:48:44.040 --> 00:48:47.250
the ozone, O3, going around--

00:48:47.250 --> 00:48:51.510
not only are really quite
harmful to your overall--

00:48:51.510 --> 00:48:55.851
to your blood vessels but
also to your brain and neurons

00:48:55.851 --> 00:48:56.350
and so on.

00:48:56.350 --> 00:49:00.570
And therefore,
sufficient antioxidants,

00:49:00.570 --> 00:49:03.570
in one form or another-- we know
that selenium works quite well

00:49:03.570 --> 00:49:06.210
in this case--

00:49:06.210 --> 00:49:08.910
really has most likely
a very good effect

00:49:08.910 --> 00:49:11.710
on preserving
cognitive function.

00:49:11.710 --> 00:49:18.810
This has been quite strongly
studied in these nematodes,

00:49:18.810 --> 00:49:24.330
in C. elegans, and also
in specific mice that

00:49:24.330 --> 00:49:26.970
had oxidative stress
and then were compared

00:49:26.970 --> 00:49:28.290
to those who did not have that.

00:49:28.290 --> 00:49:29.880
So the overall idea--

00:49:29.880 --> 00:49:31.650
I'm not going to go
into the specifics,

00:49:31.650 --> 00:49:35.050
but the overall
idea I like, yeah.

00:49:35.050 --> 00:49:36.600
- I've seen some
good work done on

00:49:36.600 --> 00:49:39.180
the antioxidant astaxanthin--

00:49:39.180 --> 00:49:40.580
- Yeah.

00:49:40.580 --> 00:49:43.080
- --and how it protects the
form of DHA that crosses

00:49:43.080 --> 00:49:45.950
the blood-brain barrier,
therefore having a benefit

00:49:45.950 --> 00:49:47.220
on the brain.

00:49:47.220 --> 00:49:51.630
But then I was curious if that
would have a vascular effect

00:49:51.630 --> 00:49:52.961
versus more of a neurological.

00:49:52.961 --> 00:49:54.960
- Yeah, that's always the
question in this case.

00:49:54.960 --> 00:49:56.130
I agree with that.

00:49:56.130 --> 00:49:56.639
It doesn't.

00:49:56.639 --> 00:49:58.680
By the way, if it works,
doesn't matter very much

00:49:58.680 --> 00:50:00.760
what the pathway is, but yeah.

00:50:00.760 --> 00:50:02.610
- Hello, my name
is Caterina Gates,

00:50:02.610 --> 00:50:06.930
and I want to thank you
for being here for us.

00:50:10.002 --> 00:50:12.450
I want to thank you for
being here for all of us,

00:50:12.450 --> 00:50:14.190
and my name is Caterina Gates.

00:50:14.190 --> 00:50:15.750
I have three short questions.

00:50:15.750 --> 00:50:18.140
Is it true what
we've heard before,

00:50:18.140 --> 00:50:24.270
going to lectures and so on,
that the Alzheimer's is apt

00:50:24.270 --> 00:50:28.050
to be passed down from mother
to daughter than from mother

00:50:28.050 --> 00:50:29.310
to sons?

00:50:29.310 --> 00:50:32.760
And is it also true
that the only way

00:50:32.760 --> 00:50:35.260
to diagnose Alzheimer's
is after death when

00:50:35.260 --> 00:50:37.310
they look at your brain--

00:50:37.310 --> 00:50:39.960
that they take it apart?

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:49.680
And the third one is what is the
commonest in the women in Japan

00:50:49.680 --> 00:50:51.750
and the women in Spain?

00:50:51.750 --> 00:50:56.130
As you said, they had, at
least, chances of having

00:50:56.130 --> 00:51:00.142
Alzheimer's or incidence
of having Alzheimer's.

00:51:00.142 --> 00:51:01.600
- Shall we start
with the last one,

00:51:01.600 --> 00:51:03.970
and then you lead me
again to the other ones?

00:51:03.970 --> 00:51:07.240
The last one-- they live
longer, women, but men

00:51:07.240 --> 00:51:09.710
as well, although there
is in both countries,

00:51:09.710 --> 00:51:11.720
the difference
between men and women.

00:51:11.720 --> 00:51:14.500
But they do not get less
Alzheimer's or dementia.

00:51:14.500 --> 00:51:17.560
In fact, when you
look at the pattern,

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:19.360
you saw the pattern with age.

00:51:19.360 --> 00:51:22.870
That's very similar whether
you see it in Japan, in Spain--

00:51:22.870 --> 00:51:24.160
there is a study in Spain--

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:26.800
and in the US or
in Western Europe.

00:51:29.690 --> 00:51:31.400
So there's basically--

00:51:31.400 --> 00:51:33.540
I don't think in this
particular instance,

00:51:33.540 --> 00:51:38.360
we cannot learn very much from
possible heterogeneity between

00:51:38.360 --> 00:51:41.960
populations, which is generally
a very good way to study

00:51:41.960 --> 00:51:43.340
particular questions.

00:51:43.340 --> 00:51:46.620
Of your two other questions,
what is your most pressing one?

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:52.700
- If it's passed down more
from mothers to daughters

00:51:52.700 --> 00:51:54.370
than mothers to sons?

00:51:54.370 --> 00:52:00.110
- OK, there is some
evidence that for longevity,

00:52:00.110 --> 00:52:02.550
in this case, for life
expectancy-- in fact,

00:52:02.550 --> 00:52:05.720
there's quite a recent
published publication on this--

00:52:05.720 --> 00:52:09.500
that this, indeed, is
in the maternal line.

00:52:09.500 --> 00:52:15.260
For dementia, I do not know of
any evidence in that respect.

00:52:15.260 --> 00:52:18.560
- That's good news because
my husband's mother had

00:52:18.560 --> 00:52:22.720
Alzheimer's, and the only way to
diagnose at the time she died--

00:52:22.720 --> 00:52:24.980
that was back in 2006--

00:52:24.980 --> 00:52:27.670
it was-- I don't know if
everyone can hear me--

00:52:27.670 --> 00:52:29.960
that it was through
just after death,

00:52:29.960 --> 00:52:31.190
if you have the brain in.

00:52:31.190 --> 00:52:34.610
I want everybody here, if
you are dealing with someone

00:52:34.610 --> 00:52:38.260
with Alzheimer's or are afraid
of maybe someone having it

00:52:38.260 --> 00:52:41.000
eventually in your
family at some point--

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:45.560
nobody will take her
brain because you

00:52:45.560 --> 00:52:49.010
had to do all that paperwork
ahead of the death here

00:52:49.010 --> 00:52:50.370
in this country.

00:52:50.370 --> 00:52:53.360
And so here she always
was an organ donor,

00:52:53.360 --> 00:52:56.520
and she wanted her brain
to go, and we wanted that,

00:52:56.520 --> 00:52:59.600
and it went to waste because
they wouldn't take it.

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:00.770
We looked at all--

00:53:00.770 --> 00:53:03.770
called every hospital where
we are here in Boston.

00:53:03.770 --> 00:53:08.481
Nobody would take it
because of the paperwork.

00:53:08.481 --> 00:53:08.980
- If--

00:53:08.980 --> 00:53:09.480
- Anyway.

00:53:09.480 --> 00:53:15.770
- --in the more general question
of paperwork and science,

00:53:15.770 --> 00:53:18.530
I'm on your side, I must say.

00:53:18.530 --> 00:53:22.130
In terms of diagnosis, making
a diagnosis, we are very close,

00:53:22.130 --> 00:53:24.350
and we are actually
quite good in making

00:53:24.350 --> 00:53:26.300
the diagnosis, also alive.

00:53:26.300 --> 00:53:28.280
And I'm not sure--
yet that is important,

00:53:28.280 --> 00:53:31.220
because that means
that being alive,

00:53:31.220 --> 00:53:34.370
we could study differences, and
we could try to find out why it

00:53:34.370 --> 00:53:35.010
is that--

00:53:35.010 --> 00:53:35.300
- Well, thank you--

00:53:35.300 --> 00:53:35.966
- --being alive.

00:53:35.966 --> 00:53:37.370
- --anyway for
everything you do.

00:53:37.370 --> 00:53:37.870
- Thank you.

00:53:40.049 --> 00:53:41.090
- My name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:41.090 --> 00:53:43.760
I'm a student in
nutritional epi.

00:53:43.760 --> 00:53:46.265
So my question is would
you please address

00:53:46.265 --> 00:53:48.870
the role of nutrition
and dietary pattern

00:53:48.870 --> 00:53:51.450
on the risk factors
you mentioned?

00:53:51.450 --> 00:53:51.950
Thank you.

00:53:54.560 --> 00:53:58.260
- I think one of the best
summaries would be to say,

00:53:58.260 --> 00:54:01.790
all dietary patterns that
are related, particularly

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:05.390
to cardiovascular disease
or vascular factors,

00:54:05.390 --> 00:54:08.270
are most likely
involved in that sense,

00:54:08.270 --> 00:54:10.940
directly or
indirectly, in dementia

00:54:10.940 --> 00:54:12.710
and Alzheimer's disease as well.

00:54:12.710 --> 00:54:14.960
This afternoon,
before I came here,

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:17.080
we had a working
group discussion

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:21.830
on carotenoids in Alzheimer's
disease and dementia--

00:54:21.830 --> 00:54:24.950
very strong evidence from
a variety of studies there.

00:54:24.950 --> 00:54:28.250
And so that would lead
then to particular trials

00:54:28.250 --> 00:54:31.010
that you could do in
which you looked then

00:54:31.010 --> 00:54:35.540
at people having those or people
not having intake of that.

00:54:35.540 --> 00:54:37.460
So yes, there are quite
a number of, I think,

00:54:37.460 --> 00:54:42.080
factors that are nutritional
factors that are possibly

00:54:42.080 --> 00:54:42.920
involved.

00:54:42.920 --> 00:54:48.950
The evidence, though, is, in
overall, not very strong yet.

00:54:48.950 --> 00:54:52.610
I emphasize yet because
I think it will be better

00:54:52.610 --> 00:54:57.650
and in the bigger
studies we have on this.

00:54:57.650 --> 00:54:59.660
I say this a bit
hesitantly, you hear,

00:54:59.660 --> 00:55:03.080
but I think one
of these chapters

00:55:03.080 --> 00:55:05.450
in the book of
dementia will certainly

00:55:05.450 --> 00:55:08.690
be nutrition or nutritional
factors in relation

00:55:08.690 --> 00:55:09.380
to the disease.

00:55:09.380 --> 00:55:12.097
It will be, I think, a bigger
chapter than the genes.

00:55:15.555 --> 00:55:16.180
- Good evening.

00:55:16.180 --> 00:55:17.680
My name is
[? Gabriela. ?] Thank you

00:55:17.680 --> 00:55:19.590
very much for your
wonderful lecture.

00:55:19.590 --> 00:55:23.020
I have a probably
very similar question.

00:55:23.020 --> 00:55:27.640
What do you think is the
role of physical inactivity

00:55:27.640 --> 00:55:35.180
as related to probably brain
volume and vascularization

00:55:35.180 --> 00:55:39.430
and probably the prevention
of Alzheimer's disease?

00:55:39.430 --> 00:55:42.100
Thank you.

00:55:42.100 --> 00:55:43.590
- I think it's big--

00:55:43.590 --> 00:55:46.980
possibly big.

00:55:46.980 --> 00:55:50.670
Physical activity is
quite strongly related

00:55:50.670 --> 00:55:53.310
to generally all
these risk factors

00:55:53.310 --> 00:55:54.810
that I mentioned
for heart disease,

00:55:54.810 --> 00:55:59.760
and thereby, indirectly at
least, also for dementia.

00:55:59.760 --> 00:56:01.560
But it's also quite
well possible,

00:56:01.560 --> 00:56:03.310
and there's increasing
evidence for that,

00:56:03.310 --> 00:56:06.700
that there's a direct neuronal
effect of physical activity.

00:56:06.700 --> 00:56:10.470
And so direct brain effect,
if I may say so, and so

00:56:10.470 --> 00:56:11.430
therefore yes.

00:56:11.430 --> 00:56:16.140
I think it's a
very good strategy

00:56:16.140 --> 00:56:22.800
to focus on physical
activity or decline

00:56:22.800 --> 00:56:27.060
and fight physical inactivity if
you want to prevent Alzheimer's

00:56:27.060 --> 00:56:28.360
disease and dementia.

00:56:28.360 --> 00:56:32.100
This is something also that
can start early in life.

00:56:32.100 --> 00:56:33.690
One of the, I
think, the tragedies

00:56:33.690 --> 00:56:36.660
of physical activity-- most
people like it very much when

00:56:36.660 --> 00:56:38.040
they are students.

00:56:38.040 --> 00:56:39.600
They go and you know and so on.

00:56:39.600 --> 00:56:41.280
And then what happens?

00:56:41.280 --> 00:56:42.240
Why does that happen?

00:56:44.970 --> 00:56:47.910
You get a family and things, and
you cannot do anything anymore

00:56:47.910 --> 00:56:48.460
and so on.

00:56:48.460 --> 00:56:51.390
But if we would continue
physical activity,

00:56:51.390 --> 00:56:54.990
being reasonably physically
active over a lifetime,

00:56:54.990 --> 00:57:00.690
I cannot give a quick estimate
of the number of patients with

00:57:00.690 --> 00:57:02.940
Alzheimer's that would save,
but I think it would be

00:57:02.940 --> 00:57:04.018
considerable.

